-- 
Crude Oil Advances in New York After Saudi Arabian Troops Enter Bahrain

-- B y   B e n   S h a r p l e s
-- 
2011-03-15T00:49:29Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-14/crude-oil-rises-68-cents-or-0-7-to-101-87-a-barrel-in-new-york-trading.html
Oil rose in  New York  as Saudi
Arabian troops moved into Bahrain as part of a regional force
from the Gulf Cooperation Council after a wave of popular
uprisings swept through countries in the Arab world.  Futures climbed as much as 0.7 percent as Saudi Arabia’s
cabinet said the kingdom has responded to a Bahraini request for
“support.” Regional unrest has toppled the leaders of Tunisia
and  Egypt  and reached Yemen, Oman and Iran. Violence in Libya
continued as forces loyal to leader  Muammar Qaddafi  carried out
air strikes against rebels in the town of Ajdabiya.  “The Middle Eastern events are still the most important
thing for the crude market,” said  Ben Westmore , a minerals and
energy economist at National Australia Bank Ltd. in Melbourne.
“I don’t think market fears have dissipated. There continues to
be violence in  Libya .”  Crude oil for April delivery gained as much as 68 cents to
$101.87 a barrel in electronic trading on the  New York
Mercantile Exchange , and was at $101.40 at 11:40 a.m. Sydney
time. Yesterday, the contract added 3 cents to $101.19. Prices
are 27 percent higher than a year ago.  Oil in New York tumbled as much as $2.69, or 2.7 percent,
to $98.47 a barrel yesterday amid speculation that Japan’s
demand may decline after the 9-magnitude earthquake struck the
world’s third-largest economy.  Brent oil for April settlement traded at $113.53 a barrel,
down 14 cents on the London-based ICE Futures Europe exchange.
The contract slid 17 cents, or 0.2 percent, to $113.67 yesterday.  Regional Unrest  Oil has surged 11 percent in New York since Jan. 14, when
the president of  Tunisia  was ousted in unrest that has affected
the Middle East and North Africa, including Saudi Arabia’s
neighbors Yemen, Oman and Bahrain. Prices climbed to a 29-month
high of $106.95 a barrel in intraday trading on March 7.  Large speculators and funds increased net-long positions,
or wagers on higher prices, by 2 percent in the seven days ended
March 8 to 311,632 futures and options, the most in records
dating back to June 2006, according to the Commodity Futures
Trading Commission’s weekly Commitments of Traders report. The
total has jumped 68 percent since Feb. 15.  An Energy Department report tomorrow may show U.S. supplies
of gasoline and heating oil probably declined last week as
refiners operated at reduced rates, according to a Bloomberg
News survey. Stockpiles of the motor fuel dropped 2 million
barrels in the seven days ended March 11 from 229.2 million a
week earlier, according to the median of seven analyst estimates
in the survey.  Japanese Refineries  The quake on March 11 shut 29 percent of domestic refining
capacity, according to Bloomberg calculations based on Petroleum
Association of  Japan  data. The country is the third-largest oil-
consuming country after the U.S. and  China .  JX-Nippon Oil & Energy Corp. closed refineries in Sendai,
Kashima and Negishi in the country’s northeastern Tohoku region
after the quake. The plants have combined processing capacity of
about 600,000 barrels a day. Cosmo Oil Co. shut its 220,000-
barrel Chiba facility following fires at liquefied petroleum gas
storage tanks.  Kyokuto Petroleum Industries Ltd. has shuttered its
175,000-barrel-a-day facility in Ichihara, near  Tokyo .
TonenGeneral Sekiyu K.K. said March 11 that it halted the major
units at its 335,000-barrel Kawasaki plant.  Japan consumed 4.42 million barrels a day of oil in 2010,
according to data from the  International Energy Agency ’s Feb. 10
Monthly Oil Market Report. China used 9.39 million barrels and
the U.S. consumed 19.25 million, the agency said.  To contact the reporter on this story:
